item.content:encoded:
Set 4 | Translational Architecture

April 18, 2023

•

Liam Walker

•

Posted on Instagram

This compilation titled “Translational Architecture” reflects the essence of my recent trip to Japan and highlights the breathtaking architectural marvels of early Japanese culture. The title brilliantly builds on my last architectural piece, emphasizing the notion of architecture transcending language and culture. I’d want to highlight the extraordinary ability of our translator, Yuki Ito (@ito._.yuki), who was critical to our immersive experience. I came back from this trip full with ideas, inspired by the cultural depth and superb workmanship of Japan’s architecture and designs.

item.content:encoded:
Set 3 | Colorless Afternoon

September 27, 2022

•

Liam Walker

•

Posted on Instagram

Many of my afternoons after school have been empty or “colorless” due to the fact that I don’t have the time or energy to make plans with friends. Last week I decided to change that, and this set, “Colorless Afternoon,” reflects a spontaneous photoshoot featuring @sorwmtil (Tamar Shuster) and @jooshuwott (Joshua Hill). The lack of color alongside the prevalent sunbeams reflects a stylistic choice that, not only, reflects the title but also emphasizes the emotionless subjects in the photo which further emphasize my experience with afternoons.

item.content:encoded:
Set 2 | Transitional Architecture

September 18, 2022

•

Liam Walker

•

Posted on Instagram

Europe as a whole contains a plethora of impressive architectural feats and this set of posts, titled “Transitional Architecture,” not only highlights these accomplishments but also serves a purpose to my page as a whole: to transition away from the warm summer aesthetic. Architecture allows us to see a civilization progression or transition through time and these posts do the same for my page. I aim to move toward a neutral white in my upcoming posts and decided that this set would accomplish that task. The color matched curve at the bottom of the images flows between each building in a manner similar to a wave. The movement cascades between each building, highlighting a certain aspect: the Eiffel Tower’s unique shape, Big Ben’s tall figure, and Hollyrood House’s unique pointed roof.

item.content:encoded:
Set 1 | Summer’s Bedroom

February 9, 2022

•

Liam Walker

•

Posted on Instagram

This set titled “Summer’s Bedroom” was inspired by a last minute idea to take photos that encapsulate my view of summer and its feel. Each self portrait contains a prevalent theme of warm whites and beams of sunlight. These elements carry warmth throughout the images and along side accents of a red shirt and green plant offer more detail and contrast. These three images show, in my opinion, a view of my favorite season: Summer.
